title: For Sale:  Swedish M41b Sniper Rifle W/ Original 4x Ajack Scope
postcontent: Here's a sniper rifle that is considered to have been perhaps the finest of its day. This is a Swedish M41B. Originally developed during WWII as the M41, the M41B is an upgraded version and like the M41 is based on the famous M96 Swedish Mauser. The sniper rifles were taken from existing stocks of M96 service rifles that were specially selected for superior accuracy. A special Jackenroll short rail scope base was then attached to the left side of the receiver to which a matching mount was hand fitted. This rifle carries the original WWII era German made AJACK 4x90 scope (Sweden remained neutral during WWII and continued some trade with Germany). The bolt handle is bent downward to avoid interference with the scope. Beginning in 1955 the M41 rifles were updated to M41B configuration which included a set screw added to the Jackenroll base to limit forward travel of the mount and the addition of a special M/55 dial type rear sight that was calibrated from 100 to 600 meters for the current service cartridge.This rifle is in very good overall condition. It was built using a Carl Gustaf M/96 originally manufactured in 1911. The receiver, barrel, bolt assembly, scope base & scope mount are correctly serial numbered to match. The buttplate is also matching however the stock is unnumbered and appears to be an excellent condition Swedish arsenal replacement. The handguard and bolt stop are non-matching which is fairly typical as most M41B rifles are found with only the matching components listed above (receiver/barrel/bolt/scope mount). The arsenal finish rates about 92-94% with some normal handling and storage wear but no rust or pitting. There is an import mark but it is stamped midway along the bottom of the barrel and is completely hidden until the action is pulled from the stock. The stock is in excellent condition and free of cracks, chips or repairs. The wood does not appear refinished but is free of any inspection stampings. This rifle is in excellent mechanical condition with everything working properly. The bore is very good with strong, bright rifling. The AJACK scope is in good working order and has bright, clear optics. The rifle comes with lens covers, a standard issue Swedish sling with quick release clip, front sight hood, and cleaning rod. This is a nice looking rifle that should be a lot of fun to shoot!Buyer pays $25.00 shipping.

title: For Sale:  Berthier M1892 EXC+ Carbine GR8 Bore WW1 3-Shot 1898
postcontent: 30 MORE PHOTOS!8mm Lebel in a short and light carbine like this is a BLAST! Literally. I went out and bought a set of dies to load cast bullets at 1800fps and my Lebel carbines are now a joy to shoot. Cheaper than 8mm Lebel ammo too. The carbine is typical of those made for WW1. First, this is NOT the M16 (or 1907/15)version you run into as well. During World War I, after complaints from combat troops regarding the limited capacity of the 3-round charger and mud ingress into the well opening, the Berthier's magazine was increased to hold a 5-round "en bloc" charger. (the extended mag you see on those) Furthermore, a hinged metal plate covering the bottom opening of the magazine well was added. The M16 versions also have a handguard on top. I have that one as well and most, if not all, have the cleaning rod channel filled (at the armory) and a stacking hook added. This M1892 has the original bayonet lug and the cleaning rod channel with no stacking hook. The 5 shot updated carbines entered WW1 late, but were used again in WW2 and in many police units until the 1960s. That makes these original M1892s less common, at least as far as I have seen over 20 years of buying them. This is also a good reason why the finish is so good as these were replaced with the updated versions beginning in 1915. This carbine was overhauled and refinished at least once in the War years and it was a Chatellerault armory made weapon. The writing on the receiver is faded, though the finish is extremely nice. You can see the armory name and Mle 1892 very clear but some other writing is not as clear but the finish is beautiful. Based on some light surface corrosion in some areas, and lack of wear anywhere, it does not look like anything recent but the finish was redone at some point in the past, likely very long ago. Since the bore is in such good condition and the bolt has little to no wear and the bolt face shows pretty much ZERO use, it is very conceivable that this beautiful finish dates back to the War years as these guns were replaced and never officially used again. This gun spent decades in storage and though I have had it just days, the lack of import marks tells me that this was brought over long ago. The previous owner had little info besides that it was in his family several decades at least. MARKINGS-- The serial number is E31399 and the E is the 5th block of numbers for the Chatellerault armory and the 2 inspector stamps are clear as well. B is the letter code for the head of the armory when the barrel was made and C was the final inspector. I did not look those up. The barrel has the MAC code (for the proper armory) and the manufacture date is very clear EXCEPT the last digit which is a 3 or 8 I believe. It was made in 1893 or 1898 and based on the E serial number block it has to be 8. The bolt head is not matched to the serial number though very few seem to be as the arsenal popped on new ones almost every rebuild or refinish. There is a beautiful cartouche just behind the trigger guard with a crown over it which I can not find. I did not take the stock off to see the other markings though it is just proof marks and dates. The bolt has a capital L in a circle in 2 locations...no clue. CONDITION-- This is an EXCEPTIONAL condition for shooting or collecting. If you are looking for all numbers matching and a museum piece, keep going and there are some sites with nice ones for $600 and up though almost all are M-16s or 1907-15s. The bore is excellent with sharp rifling (see pics) and smooth grooves. The chamber and the receiver behind it are superbly clean. The bolt, inside of the receiver, sear and bolt head are amazingly clean and the bolt and bolt head shows little to no use. The black coloring is not worn in many areas and the bolt head, which are easy to change and update, appears almost new. The rifle cocks, fires and operates smooth and slick as well as perfectly. I do NOT see the N stamp on top as almost all M16 and later ones that were still in use received the update in the 1930s, but since the 1892 carbines were no longer in use, many did not. These were long out of service when that update came about. As I shoot my reloaded ammo, it is meaningless. I would hesitate to shoot surplus ammo anyhow as the French made awesome weapons over the years but their ammo and storage of it left a lot to be desired. Most lots of surplus Lebel ammo I have are over 50% hangfires and duds. Scary stuff sometimes. I would check if the Prvi ammo made now is OK to use in non N marked guns. Possible, but check to be sure. The cleaning rod does not look original but it looks so good there, I left it. It was actually for popping out stuck cases rather than cleaning and nobody today uses them. If you want a proper modern version or original, it will cost you. Original bayonets are available on Ebay for $80 to $100. This gun may not have all of the clearest markings but the finish is superb. Not all matching, but few are. It is in fantastic condition with a great bore and if you want a superb looker and shooter, THIS IS IT. Outstanding blue-black finish with no fading or wear. The bolt also has a superb finish which is all original. It has been gone over and detailed here for you with loads of photos as well. SHIPPING-- This will ship as a 10 pound package by Fedex Ground or Priority (my choice depending on your location) for $36.00 Paypal is fine but contact me first as the address is different. Also, payment must be sent with NO FEES so use "send money to family or friends". Personal checks are fine and I will not hold it more than the couple of days it takes to deposit. Please send a good one
